Friday, 2/21/2014 Morning Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 8.58 Miles
Comments 800, 10 min. Tempo, 2x400

Felt a bit tired during the warmup and strides but fine during workout. Hydrated well yesterday. 800 was a good hard effort but slow; turnover felt sluggish and probably could/should have pushed harder in the middle. "Tempo" felt like a training run and started 2 x mile pace 400s fully recovered. 400s were quick but felt strong and good form. Overall the workout went well, recoveries were long and the effort felt spread out

Monday, 2/24/2014 Afternoon Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 7.07 Miles
Comments 4x200, 6x400, 4x200

Hardest workout (/effort?) so far this season. Generally felt slow and hard-- apparently really not used to faster stuff especially on the roads, so need to watch my recovery. First 200s were OK, took a while to get going. 400s were all over the place (on Maiden, so odd reps were slightly uphill) and by myself. Randomly dropped a :62 unknowingly on the 2nd rep and definitely paid for it afterward, pretty much dead at 250 on the last four 400s but got into one of those cool "wow, this hurts but I don't care because I'm not thinking straight" zones and floated through mentally. Last 200s reasonably good focusing on form. Stride felt choppy and foot strike felt a little hard (maybe over-striding a bit/speed on roads). Cold/windy so took me a while to catch my breath in between reps. Biggest takeaway-- I need sharpening and this is it, may be hard but this kind of mile pace stuff is what will get me ready for Nationals.

Of note: noticeably less sleep now that school started again; something to watch

Wednesday, 2/26/2014 Afternoon Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 7.5 Miles
Comments HPHS 3 x (2x200, 800)

Workout at Hartford Public. Did it in spikes and sockless which was a mistake on the tight turns (160m track). By the end, the tops of my feet were raw which undoubtedly contributed to my mediocre 800 splits. Hamstring tightness also popped up on the turns and legs generally tired but overall a good effort. Friday, 3/7/2014 Afternoon Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 8 Miles
Comments 3x (800, 200, 200)

Fairly light workout after US meeting. Hamstring tight at times but nothing serious and overall a good workout. 800s were based off of watch (.50 miles) so a bit long and slower splits but felt good aerobically and not bad legs. 200s were at mile pace then fast, worked it down throughout the workout and felt strong. Pretty good core/lifting workout at home after. My splits were incredibly linear today (2:25.9 in the first "800", so technically 3-second decreases each set! 200s were perfectly linear!) and overall a feel good day.

Friday, 3/14/2014 Afternoon NO RUN - OFF [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance --    -- Not running miles
Comments Nationals Day 1

Was planning to do an easy 2 miles or so after school then strides, drills, stretching to prep for nationals. After feeling pretty bad at school, decided to forego running for today. Napped on the ride up to NY then headed to the Armory to see our DMR (Zach, Reid, Chris, Ari).

Nationals was cool. The Armory was way older and smaller than it seems during the Millrose live feed but an awesome atmosphere nonetheless. Everyone in the field went out too hard (not surprising) and our DMR was 10:26, a bit disappointing but fun to watch.

I was happy to be a spectator for a few reasons: 1) Seeing everyone go out hard then be disappointed taught me an obvious lesson, 2) The Armory was HOT and I was prepared the next day, 3) Valuable to see what it would be like for me so I had less to think about leading up to my race.

Afterward, went to Chipotle (my first time) on Broadway with the Aldaves and Dan Magin then headed back to the hotel.

DMR video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eg9Bfncr2I0&index=2&list=FLRyfQVxuj1RVDaZg5IPQWvg

Saturday, 3/15/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 5 Miles
Comments Nationals Day 2-- 4xMile 2nd Leg

Headed back to the Armory for 4xMile Heat 1 at 12:40. Slept pretty well length-wise, but kept waking up and didn't sleep at all from 2-4AM. Didn't feel terrible sickness-wise before the race, took cold medicine and Advil before, felt fine in the pit and wasn't concerned with my health when racing.

Clocked unofficially (no official result splits for a 4x1609m of course) at 4:25 (5 sec PR over GHI Outdoor 1600, 9 sec PR over Yale Mile "triple"). Very pleased with the time, but I just raced to compete and had no idea what my splits were; I'm most pleased with my tactics and competitiveness. Looking back at the race video, my form wasn't great (head wasn't steady towards end and L arm needs work still). My head, throat, and ears really hurt afterward, probably the result of the dry air and semi-sickness; I also didn't have an appetite and didn't eat anything from breakfast to like 9PM back home. Really nice cooldown down by the Hudson, feeling satisfied that I had ran the best I could under the circumstances.

Overall, Nationals was a great experience, and I was really fortunate that I had the opportunity to go. All things considered, I probably had it the easiest of the Hall guys (in terms of freshness and how the race played out) to run fast. I see a lot of similarities to New Englands in XC; I really wasn't very focused on how I felt running-wise in both cases and ended up just getting out there and racing (and they were 2 of my best races... interesting).

For now, I'll take the next week off from running then outdoor starts a week from Monday. Not sure if I'll lift, do drills or core or strides, or do stretching during the break, but I'm planning to have a big emphasis on that during outdoor.

Video of 4xMile:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vuyeLmm5cKI&index=3&list=FLRyfQVxuj1RVDaZg5IPQWvg

Drove up to the Albany Res with Ari and Zach. Overcast day and kinda humid but nice. Slow warm-up on trails then 40 min tempo at goal 6:00 pace around the loop. Felt tired again but the workout went pretty well, hamstring tight at times. Got into a good rhythm in the middle, last two miles started to get tired legs-wise (and I think my form started to falter) but I probably could have kept it up to 45 min. Slow cool-down on mountain bike trail after. I like that we did this workout and I hope to revisit it; unfortunately, running kinda took a back seat this week along with sleep. I wish I had prepared more for this workout mentally and physically because I think that I could have made it a really good one, great strength effort nonetheless. Also, starting to respect marathoners more... I'm still a long way from 26.2 at sub-6 (2:37).

Splits: 5:49, 6:03, 5:57, 5:46, 5:48, 6:06, 4:26 [for .73] (Average 5:57)

Probably 12ish tmrw easy then 4-6 barefoot hopefully on Sunday.

Nice temperature and not windy today. Team stuff then quicker workout alone, but I'm glad I was. I felt pretty lousy and lethargic before and was expecting the worst--it ended up going pretty well. Tuesday, 4/29/2014 Afternoon Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 9.46 Miles
Comments Home Meet vs. Northwest

Cool and a bit windy and drizzling at times today. Pretty good meet overall; 1600, 800, 3200; 1st, 1st, 2nd--13 pts (no Ari today and Zach is just coming back). Didn't feel great before warming up but felt much better after stretching. Pretty much low 4:40ish pace in the 1600 with Zach then closed pretty hard. After talking with Mosca and Ari earlier, I knew that I wanted to get the 1600 states qualifier out of the way eventually (just in case); when I heard our split at 1200 and was feeling good, I just went for it. Very relaxed and controlled for 4:40 pace, a good sign! 800 went alright, went out harder than I intended maybe because I was cold. I was aiming for a slight negative split and :62 felt good so I just kept it hard the second lap. Paced Kaback to 10:40ish PR in the 3200. We were a bit slow through the mile so I tried to pull him along in the second mile; I kept looking back to check where he was and try to encourage him which was weird to do in a "race" (and made me self-conscious that spectators would think I was showing off haha). As a tempo, the 3200 was pretty good, legs kinda tired by then but I don't remember it being a challenge aerobically (maybe because my focus was on Kaback?). Overall, felt really good when running fast today. This surprised me and made me want to run faster (because it felt so good). I think I probably shouldn't have gone as hard in the 800 and 1600 but I hate going slow when I feel fresh. Good mileage for the day, but I kinda wish we could have just done a normal workout instead of a meet today.

Chilled at 4:40 pace in the 1600 then closed hard, I was at the losing end (4th) after that 800. So many guys PRed enormously in the 1600 which was cool. Tired for the 3200 and did kinda a faster tempo for 3rd; legs heavy by then but alright as a workout. Quite high mileage today and definitely the closest to what I'll call a "race" so far this season. Probably will go shorter and easier tmrw and long on Saturday with Sunday off to keep mileage low for GHI.

Saturday, 5/10/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 1 Mile
Comments Warm and humid when I ran, but I don't remember realizing it while racing. Weird race/experience, not really sure my thoughts so I'll just summarize...

Legs didn't feel great this morning, some lingering soreness when I stretched but nothing bad--just generally didn't feel super fresh. Warmup was hot and I was having doubts about how I'd do in the heat. I can't remember my thought process after then. I had stepped in a huge puddle and one of my shoes got soaked, so I guess I just stopped caring about how I felt and raced on instinct. Looking back, I don't even know what I was thinking during the race. I got out pretty well and was in the pack at 400 (:67ish), which was slower than I wanted (I had pre-determined that I would try to split :65s and see how it went). I think I moved to the front at 500ish in then just gaped the field by 800 and ended up winning by 2ish seconds. Mosca said my 3rd lap was big and I definitely negative split, but none of it was conscious on my part and I didn't see any other splits. I was half expecting someone to catch me in the last 300, but no one showed up. I guess the weird part was that no one went with me (I really wasn't going that fast) and I ended up running it alone. I'm pleased with 4:24 (1600 PR, but a little slower than my 4:25 full mile) but based on how I felt after and my general recollection of the race, I know I can and will run faster. It would have been cool to have run a breakout time (4:20 or below) and I think I am in shape to and could have today with a faster start and actual kick. Odd race mentally for the most part, but felt real good running at mile pace. The Courant reporter interviewed me after which was new for me but I can't imagine I'll get used to it. I also think this is my first invitational win (I won heat 2 of the 1600 at GHI last year) and I didn't really think I would win (until 200 to go that is).

Saturday, 5/17/2014 Night Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 2 Miles
Comments Danbury Dream 2 mi

Very good race conditions, 8:15 at night, no wind, cool. Mild cold symptoms during the day before but prepared as best I could. Didn't really notice it during the race, I just dried up quickly and my chest might have burned more than usual. Very small race and not that deep, so I ran the second mile alone for the most part. Felt a little quick through the mile, but that was my plan--go out harder and bring it home with what I had left. I'm not too happy with how I ran the second mile, and I will work on staying focused and pushing laps 5-7. My sinuses and head hurt afterward and I didn't really feel like eating anything. On the ride back I had a headache at first, but then we started talking about relativity and it disappeared haha!

So because of my sub-par indoor 3200s, running 9:35 (full 2 mile) beat my best 3200m by 18 sec. An 18+ sec PR sounds good, but this was my first 2 mile where I feel that I raced close to my fitness. Had I felt better the last few days, I probably would have raced more aggressively; when I feel 100% health-wise, sub 9:30 for 3200m is reasonable and hopefully I'll run faster with competition. Overall, this was a pretty cool meet and I'm definitely glad that it was pushed back a day. Mileage super low this week, so I'll keep it a down week and try to recover.

Saturday, 5/24/2014 Morning Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 4.48 Miles
Comments 3 x (2x200,400,300)

Fine weather today, good temp for workout and no sun. Haircut at 8 then 9 AM practice at Hall. Pretty important workout as far as I can tell, good fitness indicator, spiked up for the first time in a workout in a while. The spikes probably skewed my times and effort, but I'll be racing in them so not too concerned. 200s at 800 pace were very consistent, :29-:30, felt alright but hard to get in a groove. 400s at mile pace (:65 goal) also felt pretty good, noticeably slower and more controlled than the 200s. 300s ended up being around 800 pace, stayed composed throughout but would start to feel lactic in the last 100m. Recovery jogs felt comfortable pace-wise and I was recovered well for each rep; I think I could have handled one more set with similar splits. I retied my spikes after the second set because they were rubbing on the tops of my feet--annoying but not painful enough to mess with my stride. Definitely improved throughout the workout, which felt surprisingly short and really not overly fatiguing (not what I usually say about speed work). Overall, this workout went really well, felt composed throughout and within myself running fast, good mental focus, so nice to have an empty track. Taking tmrw off, but I don't really think I need an off day, feeling good the last few days running-wise and still a lingering cough but not bad.

Wednesday, 5/28/2014 Afternoon wu/cd [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 9 Miles in 1:03:00 [7:00 per mile]
Comments CCC West Championship at Simsbury

3 miles total warmup, some on track, some at Stratton Brook. Light stretching and strides after. 1 mile easy between 1600 and 800. 5 miles total cooldown around turf, lot, and Stratton Brook. Started moving with Ari in the last 3 mile segment, probably between 6:20-6:35.

Much cooler and kinda windy out today, may have been factor in overall no one, including myself, running fast. 4x800 didn't go as well as I'd hoped. Went in with expectations for 2:01 or below but just didn't seem to have it as the 2nd leg today. Legs a bit fatigued after but not terrible. 1600 was frustrating and I don't think I ran it well. Between the 800 and 1600, I had this weird sharp pain in my lower back and the back of the hip joint, almost like it had cracked out of place (overstretching? is that a thing?). I wasn't sure what to do for a bit then ran on it and it improved, not an issue when racing or cooling down, but I can feel it now when I move a certain way... I'll keep an eye on it.

Overall, not a great meet. I guess I got the job done but it didn't feel good. I hoped that the 1600 would be a fast race where I could run close to 4:20 and then forget about the mile, and it didn't happen. Gotta gear up for L's on Monday where I'll get redemption for today. Skipped the junior awards night but I didn't really want to go anyway.

Thursday, 6/5/2014 Afternoon Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 8.38 Miles
Comments 6 Lap Tempo, 5-4-3-2-1 Cutdown

Comfortable conditions today, ended up being cloudy most of the workout. Very good workout today. Link Crew until 4:30 then warmed up to St. Joe's (6:45 pace without trying, but didn't feel great) because of a lax states game. A few strides/plyos and jogging then 6 lap tempo at 5:20 pace, felt controlled and good. 2 min break and quick switch into spikes. 500 and 400 around 4:20 pace, recoveries were relatively short before them but felt good (confirms I should have broke 4:20 this season). After that, stopped continuously running and would jog and walk longer recoveries for last 3 fast reps. 300 felt good but didn't know where to stop at St. Joe's track, 200 also very good. 100 felt pretty pointless because it was so short, my first timed 100 though. Ran home with a lightweight hiking backpack I had in my closet holding my spikes; kinda annoying but I could do it again if I ever need to. My first backpack run. Overall, couldn't have gone much better today. I think I could have handled a little more, either in the tempo or maybe something like 5-4-4-3-3-2, but Opens on Monday so whatever. Back was good during the day, no trouble at all during the workout (yay!), a little tightness after the workout.

Monday, 6/9/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 0.5 Miles
Comments 1:57!!!!! Broke 2 finally, 4 second PR. Not an official split, so I'll have to go to the race video to confirm it. ...(3 weeks later finally watched the video which is useless for getting times so I'm calling it 1:58. http://www.nfhsnetwork.com/events/95792)

Felt okay before, light drizzle and overcast. Conditions were good, heat or humidity never an issue at all. 2nd leg. Got the baton from Zach in 5th with a slight gap between me and a string of 4 guys in front of me. Tested trying to catch them immediately in the first 100, but wasn't making a dent, passed by Windsor by 200. Moved up a bit I think on the home stretch and came through 400 around :57 I believe, now totally in contact with the leading teams. Moved out off the turn and passed pretty much everyone with 300 to go. Even with Darien for the lead from 200 to 150 then pulled away and gapped a little, handed off baton in first to Chris. We went on to place 2nd in an excruciating final 50m, where Ostberg confirmed that he is a beast. 7:55 team time, 4 second school record.

Overall, this was a perfect setup for me, and I executed. Reminds me of nationals 4xmile so much, where Zach handed off to me behind a pack and I just subconsciously closed the gap and took the lead. I can't believe I ran 1:57! I think anyone on our relay would have run equally as well had they been in my position... I lucked out again I guess. Legs felt choppy for the first 200, but after that pretty much everything was on instinct, which worked out. First time since Opens last year where I had someone near me in a 4x8 with 200 to go, and it helped having the competition for sure.

Saturday, 6/14/2014 Morning wu/cd [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.01 Miles
Comments New Englands 4x8

Slow warm up and cooldown around Bridgewater State campus. Pretty humid conditions and the stadium was hot and smelled like grilled meat and smoke. Last race with our signature relay team for the past 2 years, a lot of other CT/New England teams went to Nationals.

Outdoor season and Junior year ended here, both of which went really well as a whole. 400- :54.6; 800- 1:58*; 1600- 4:24, 3200- 9:30, Class L 4x8 champs, state 4x8 runner-ups. My speed progressed incredibly well this season without me even focusing on it. Brought PRs for literally every distance down by a lot, but I think I could have ran a faster 3200 fresh and know I could have been 4:22 or below if I had ran another 1600 (looks like I have to wait till winter now). Training was very consistent all season, one day where I missed a workout for sickness, healthy all around otherwise. I have more reflecting to do but for now a week off and mental reset for XC summer training (don't have a plan yet).

Thursday, 7/24/2014 Morning Hill Training [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 8.01 Miles in 52:24 [6:32 per mile]
Comments 5xUplands

Humid but nice. Decided to wear the Road N0s to get used to working out in them. Biked to Fern Park (removed about 3 running miles total) so I could spend more time in the hills. Short run over to Uplands where I did 5 x the 400m segment (from Midlands to the mailbox over the crest) with a long "recovery" on the Canal-Westmont-Midlands loop. Kept it around what felt like 5k effort on the uphill, though it varied from 5:25-50 pace throughout, and around 6:35-40 on the recoveries. Not really a pure hill workout--more of a fartlek I guess--but solid effort. This should help with my hill strength at least, might revisit this with surging over the top for 600m total. Focused on strong form, maintaining cadence, legs felt good considering how much of a quad-shredder this should have been with the biking too. Good stuff.

Saturday, 8/2/2014 Morning Long Run [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 15.01 Miles in 1:30:32 [6:01 per mile]
Comments Ocean Beach 15

9 AM race, rainy and cool. 1 mile warmup on the course, 11.6 miles in the race with Ari and Zach, add on after with Ari to hit 15. Treated the race as a workout, didn't really stick to my 5k cutdown plan but went very very well. Went out in 6:03, hung around with a pack for a few more miles around that pace then eased away and naturally picked it up to the finish, no one passed us and we kept picking off people. Average for the race was 5:44 pace, ~:66 min, 13.1 split was 1:17:21 (10 minute PR). I guess 5:50s and below is approaching the tempo zone for an 11 mile run but it didn't feel like it at all. Breathing was never stressed and always controlled aerobically, I think I could have closed the last few in sub-5:30 and felt fine. Crazy when comparing this to our 40 min Res tempo in outdoor at 5:55ish pace, but **I can't forget that these were perfect conditions when looking back in-season**. Couldn't have asked for a better run, good indicator, good workout, good fun, cool day at Billing's house with alumni and other runners after, ride home with Conway and Aguila.

Mile splits:
6:03, 5:58, 5:50, 5:55, 5:49, 5:44, 5:34, 5:51, 5:50, 5:34, 5:27, then last .6 fast

Leaving for Maine early tmrw morning, back on Wed, no r2w until then. Hopefully running isn't too hard to fit in, will likely save quality for later in the week. Probably 5 tmrw, 74 for the week.

Comments 8 x 2 min Fartlek

Tuesday, 8/19/2014 Morning Fartlek [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 9.47 Miles
Comments 6 x 2:30 Fartlek

9 AM capt prac but kind of warm. Biked to and from Hall again, 3rd fartlek in the 1:30-2:00-2:30 progression. 1st 4 reps were on the course, last two were around the track (in retrospect, I wish I stayed on the grass), 2 min recoveries. Reps were close to 5 min pace on the course, slightly faster on the track, recoveries were 6:40 and below except the 2nd to last one was slower for me. I felt pretty good on the grass, in control but my breathing was a little off; my legs and stride felt worse on the track and it started to feel like a formal 6x800 workout. Overall, continuing to serve well as a transition toward 5k pace, I'm still thinking long term. 10 min barefoot cooldown on turf w/Ari then a barefoot burma with Conway who was passing through.

Comments 6 mi Tempo

Went straight from Link Crew to Res 6 for tempo on the loop. Ended up just doing 6 miles (~1-2/3 loops) rather than 40 min or 2 loops b/c I wasn't feeling terrific. ~2 mile warmup OAB on the trail, 6 miles in 34:41 (5:46 average), cooldown OAB to hit 10. Tuesday, 9/9/2014 Afternoon Dual Meet [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 9.8 Miles
Comments Simsbury/NW Dual Meet

Perfect conditions, 70s and comfortable, home course was dry. 2 mi loop warmup + a burma and some more, light drills/strides and rope stretching, dual meet race, broken up cooldown culminating in a 2 mi loop. Didn't feel great beforehand and warming up, I guess normal pre-race feeling, I was anxious (for a dual meet) before but it turned out there was nothing to worry about. Felt good during the race, Achilles is all better, got out well and stayed relaxed the entire time. Got a little of the post-race legs feeling afterward, but wasn't drained by the faster 1st mile, solid effort today and felt phenomenal for the time I ran. Almost sad to say I PRed by 10ish seconds without going all out... I wasn't expecting today's effort to be faster than anything I ran last season, but its good for confidence, pretty much a quick mile then 2 mi harder tempo.

Mile with Ari and a Simsbury freshman in 4:57 (feeling controlled, 5:10 effort) and already knew we had 1-2 sealed, 2 miles in 10:16 I think after consciously starting to chill out, cruised in the last mile still controlled, final time 16:17. The varsity and team overall looked phenomenal today, Ari ran 15:44 (huge CR)... the conditions were definitely a factor, but I can't believe we all ran so quick. Easily beat Simsbury (1-2-4-5-6). To be honest, not a hugely taxing day; thought we would do something after but we didn't.

Saturday, 9/20/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.1 Miles
Comments Didn't get off great from the line, but I wasn't looking to go out hard so it worked out. Relaxed the first mile, slowly moving up in the pack and not pushing the hills, felt controlled, composed, and confident. By the top of the second hill and around on the pavement it was basically Ari, Randy, Palmer, me, not sure who was behind. Passed Palmer near the end of the pavement feeling good, started to push up the third hill to try to gap him, ended up catching Randy pretty easily, surged past him and over the top of the hill hard. Caught Ari by the trails, we ran together for a little but he eventually gapped me near the end of the trails and closed on the gravel a lot faster than I did. I really only started working from the trails to the finish, I was waiting to get caught by Randy on the gravel but ended up finishing 2nd behind Ari in 16:19. Conway's old CR (the legendary "course cut" one) was 16:16, pretty cool I was that close, now Hall has top three fastest times on Simsbury's home course.

Overall, very pleased with today. Strategically, I think I ran the best I could; competitively, I think I ran well but there wasn't really too much head-to-head racing. Mentally, just let things happen and tried to go by feel, however I think I relaxed mentally too much when I was running with Ari, would have been cool to force myself to stick with him and work together in the last 600m. The first two miles felt controlled and comfortable (which I think our training has prepared us well for so far), last mile is where future training will have the biggest benefits--especially last 800. 200s/400s on Thursday didn't seem to affect anything, legs felt good racing, very good on the hills. Pleased with the result too, we went 1-2 for the second year in a row (I would have been happy with top-4), wasn't expecting to be anywhere near Conway's record (I ran 17:20 last year), conditions were very good for fast times today though.

Saturday, 9/27/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.1 Miles
Comments Plan was to get out well and run in the front pack, which I did. Never really felt relaxed in the first mile, but I was in fine position. Maintained on the hills but legs didn't feel great, I was able to pass a few guys after the top of the ski hill and was battling for 5th place on the downhill. Workout Data:
Total distance 9.42 Miles
Comments Conard 5k and 2x1k

Comfortable weather, a little windy, course was a bit soft but not bad. Last Hall XC dual meet, got my first and only home course win (planned with Ari of course). 2.5 mi warmup after typical pre-meet prep, first two miles at 5:20 pace, last mile hard, 5 min rest, 2x1k on lower burma with 3 min rest, 2 mi loop+ cooldown. I didn't get the exact mile splits, but from 2.1 to 3.1 was 4:59 and the total time was 16:32. The first two miles felt pretty good and relaxed but I was breathing hard on that last mile, under control though. The 1ks went by quickly, 3:09, 3:09 (about 5 min pace), considered doing one more but decided to keep something in the tank with Wickham on Saturday. Felt good overall, went by quickly mentally, wore XC flats today, we went 1-2-3-4-5-7... three undefeated seasons in dual meets!

Thursday, 10/9/2014 Afternoon Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 9.65 Miles
Comments 4 x (2x200, 400)

Nice day, a little windy. 4 mile warmup on Richmond and mile loop, basically alone for everything today but I was fine for that... I like doing these more informal workouts by myself. Repeated the pre-Stratton Brook 4 x (2x200, 400) on the track progressing down to about mile pace, I loosened up well today and felt good running quicker. Last time I was aiming for 33-34 and 66-68; similar today but a little faster on the 200s and naturally took less recovery. Stayed pretty relaxed and form felt strong and controlled, recoveries weren't too long but felt right, I didn't want this to turn into an anaerobic effort and it wasn't by any means--not too concerned with splits and overall informal like last time. Shorter cooldown on the mile loop and around Hall.

Saturday, 10/11/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.1 Miles
Comments As mentioned, I didn't feel too great before but was confident that I'd improve when things got going. I got out pretty well (it was only a 100 man field) and was in a front pack until around the mile. By then, Randy and Ari had formed a bit of a gap that ended up growing a ton, I ran from the mile to 2.5 mile pretty much all alone. I knew I had gone out harder than I should have and my 2nd mile was definitely slower, never really got out of a low-energy funk. Around the stone wall a pack caught me, I ran with them for a little then tried to put on a surge to pull away from them, didn't work and I basically finished at the back of that pack.

On the soft downhill after the mile I started to feel a little tightness in my upper left hamstring, a lot like during indoor. For the rest of the race, my stride felt unbalanced and a little off, especially on the hills and muddy parts. In the last mile or so when conditions got pretty bad, it was pretty easy to back off and lose competitiveness. Not too pleased about this, but hopefully backing off a little now will help later on. After the race most of my left leg felt off, hamstring was tight, hip was kinda tight, and me knee felt weird when walking. I iced later on with a homemade ice pack (ice and salt, a very bad idea in retrospect) on my bare skin and burned a bit of my upper leg.

Overall, I didn't feel like I raced strong or smart (my pre-race goals). I honestly think I should have been 3rd in this race. I should have been able to go with Randy and Ari through at least two miles then it would have been sweet to battle with Randy for 2nd and try to go 1-2. Nonetheless, a very good team performance for us, very good improvement. Now it's time to break 16 on this course.

Comments CCCs

2.69 warmup to the usual places.
3.60 cooldown around watching JV race then a few loops of the Green Monster.

Kinda warmer and humid today, course conditions were good, much better than the invite. Stretched/prepped hamstring well before and typical warmup stuff after, legs weren't feeling great in general and not very fresh at all when racing--maybe from all the extra static stretching and stuff I've been doing. Starting tmrw, I'll begin to work on strengthening my hamstring and probably hips. I'll continue to stretch, roll with a tennis ball, and ice as I have been... 10 days to Class LL. Also, our mileage has dropped per week as planned, in the last few days the pace of the runs has got slower too--at the moment I'm focused on the hamstring though.

Wednesday, 10/15/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.1 Miles
Comments As I mentioned, I stayed very patient today, never in full race/competition mode. I was confident that if I ran smart and was careful, my fitness would help take care of the top-3 finish I was looking for. The race played out very similarly to how I had envisioned/planned for.

Got off the line right as I should have, settled in pretty soon with a front pack (minus Ari and Palmer) and began relaxing early. Comfortable through the mile, backed off where I thought I should on the downhills, stayed relaxed up the Green Monster in a group of Randy, me, Stoker, passed Palmer shortly after. Overall, time doesn't mean much to me but good to see it was better than the Invite. As a whole, pleased with today; we accomplished what we wanted as a team and I accomplished what I wanted running smart and controlled to stay healthy. That being said, today wasn't an easy day where I just coasted, I did work hard (at somewhere less than all-out 5k effort and pace) but purposely limited, more of a legs day than lungs day.

Saturday, 10/25/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.1 Miles
Comments Box 2, got out right where I needed to and felt pretty good. Ari went ahead immediately then a bit of a gap to Randy then a pack with me. Stuck around until the mile feeling pretty good, felt strong past the finish and around to the Green Monster. Kinda lost contact by the playground and started to feel my shin on the downhill after 2 miles. Passed a Ridgefield kid at the stone wall, but last 1k felt pretty weak and slow, basically no significant kick in the final straight and stride felt a bit unbalanced. Sucked so bad seeing a Cheshire freshman get the last all-state envelope in front of me in the chute. I know I'm in shape to run 16:20 and compete with Hixson and Randy.

Form just didn't feel good when I got tired. Looking back, not great mentally when things started to hurt... maybe I wasn't as confident with this last week of training not being great. I was kinda nervous about having hamstring issues but I still should have been able to focus for less than 17 minutes and stay strong.

Ari won unchallenged in 15:48. 4th place team (beat Staples by a little). Amity, Danbury, Ridgefield in front of us. 2nd team time (mainly thanks to Ari).

Saturday, 10/25/2014 Afternoon wu/cd [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 4.9 Miles in 35:29 [7:14 per mile]
Comments LLs

Warmer weather than I expected but not bad. Felt pretty good before, 2.58 typical warmup but lots of traffic, lighter on the rope stretching and drills, felt alright on the line. 2.32 cooldown with Ben around on the course, legs felt okay. Wearing the v2s for the first time was fine, felt good in them and wasn't worrying about it.

Race started out alright and I was feeling good until the bottom of the green monster. That was pretty much the end of feeling good and the last mile felt pretty wimpy. Some point around two miles, not sure exactly where, the front of my left shin got really tight and lost contact with being competitive. Finished in 10th but I know I was better than 10th in that race. I ran faster at CCCs which sucks, just overall not where I wanted to be today. Afterward, my shin stayed locked up for a while, didn't really hurt but it just felt like something bigger was wrong. Probably caused in some way by my hamstring... maybe weakness made me heelstrike a bit on downhills which put more pressure on my shin than usual.

Did some pretty good strengthening for the hamstring later, good core and functional strength stuff too. Took (what I tried to make) an ice bath, but wasn't very cold and didn't feel like it did anything.

Friday, 10/31/2014 Afternoon Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.1 Miles
Comments Legs felt good before, strides felt smooth and no typical pre-race feeling. Box in the middle, got out very well (4th place around 800 in) but it felt right and I was out of trouble (opposite of Opens last year). Felt strong at the mile and a 15:50 pack passed me before the Green Monster, kept form much better up the hill and through two miles. Awesome to have guys around me to legitimately contend with from 2 miles to the end. Stayed mentally competitive and in race mode with surges and definitely pushed myself the hardest this season. In 11th coming out of the woods, passed by Soggard, closed the last 300ish hard but passed by Hickson just before the line (hadn't seen him the entire race). Didn't think about time at all until I saw the clock at 16:08 and was happy. So many guys to beat from 15:55 to 16:08, now I remember what it's like to actually race guys and race all out--I like it!

Looking back, I was very competitive but also didn't really take any risks. I suppose I could have tried to latch onto the pack that broke 16, but one of my goals for today was to have better form and strength which I definitely accomplished. Also, from the woods to the finish it took too long to get into "kick" mode, I was winding things up but could have gone earlier probably. I was nervous on the downhill after the mile and after the 2 mile that my shin would start to tighten up but nothing developed, likely due to better form. At this point, I want New Englands to feel the same physically but take greater risks and really go for it in my last Wickham race.

Saturday, 11/8/2014 Morning wu/cd [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 5.77 Miles in 45:56 [7:57 per mile]
Comments New Englands

Cooler weather beforehand but turned out to be perfect XC racing temperature. The course was a little soft and generally slower than Friday. 2.66 warmup to the typical places but went to the maze with the guys then more with Ari, 3.11 cooldown slow with the guys again then more with Ari, through the maze, stopped for a little to reflect at the "take it all in, boys" spot. Last of my races at Wickham. I know I'll be back, but I'll miss what it feels like racing XC there and all the pre/post-race stuff. I'll look back on the team memories fondly and try to make the most of them now while I can. Luckily, I went out on a high note at Opens and today...

I ran 16:09 again in slower conditions but moved up from 13th in CT to 10th in New England. The first two miles were probably a little slower than Opens but the last mile was definitely faster. Pretty sweet to beat a bunch of CT guys for the first time and have some out of state competition too. Would have been so sick if I broke 16 on top of all this, but I'm not complaining. This was the best race place-wise of my life--no question. Based on how it felt though, it wasn't "physically" amazing; I think I used all my fitness to the max but it just didn't feel like it. Being 10th on stage at East Catholic was cool but it's just one race; great to have a confirmation that I can race and beat these guys. Another example of me running my best in big races (Indoor nationals 4xmile 4:25, Outdoor states 4x8 2nd leg, this). 10th at New Englands is pretty sick.

Saturday, 11/8/2014 Morning Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 3.1 Miles
Comments Box 27 near the middle, a few strides before but I wasn't feeling as good as before Opens. Got out fine, farther back than Opens but right where I needed. Found Oliver Hixson from Staples on the downhill in the first mile and basically ran right with him until past two miles. Felt alright at the mile and around to the finish, I was hearing people say 20th-25th. Just stuck with Hixson up the Green Monster and to the two mile mark. I wasn't really feeling great all this time and was expecting to have to race for top 20ish in the last mile and hopefully not fall back. Mentally, I kinda thought I was going to have a disappointing race at this point, but I decided to tough it out and make it hurt to stick with the pack past 2 miles. Probably 17-20th at 2 miles.

I don't know what happened in the last mile. I guess I had just stopped thinking and used the last four years of work and used Butterfield to finish my XC career how it should. From the bottom of the hill to the tree to the stone wall I just started rolling. It wasn't even conscious, didn't even feel it in my legs. No one passed me in the last mile, I was just inching up past guys, first Randy then Van der Els then I saw Spencer Brown a little ahead on the trails. Kept passing people then came out of the woods only behind Brown. I have no recollection of how I felt physically through all this, I was just going. I guess I didn't die around the fields and then started kicking around the last tree. Went past Brown on the final straight and just went hard waiting to be passed right before the finish. Crossed the line in tenth and the the clock at 16:0x. Felt pretty bad in the chute, shook hands/congratulated Ostberg then just wandered around kinda stunned. It turns out there was a pack chasing me up to the finish but no one caught me and I never looked back or knew it. Ended up just sitting down on the grass alone then Butterfield came over and I cried a little.

Thursday, 11/20/2014 Afternoon Interval Workout [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 8 Miles
Comments 5x1k

Cool day but nice again. Workout in shorts and short sleeves with gloves and a hat (probably my go-to at regionals). Richmond warmup, cooldown loop cooldown. Ran the workout with Everett! Very pleased with how things felt and was good mentally, especially since we were working together. Stayed consistent in the first four, ran the last one a little harder. Nonetheless, felt like a very good fitness day, form felt strong. Only thing I would change would be to get after it more in the 5th rep.

Saturday, 11/29/2014 Morning Race [ Top ]
Workout Data:
Total distance 6 Miles
Comments Footlocker Northeast Regional

Slept alright, took the train to the course, conditions were cold but the course was good (wet in the first 400 but fine otherwise). Didn't time the warmup (by accident) so I decided to not time the cooldown either, felt alright pre-race but in retrospect I don't think I warmed up enough. Given the cold temperature, I don't think my usual strides and drills were enough, and I think it impacted my race. Cooled down easy around the perimeter with Sam Katten; a great contingent of Hall guys came down which was cool. Ben ran really well in the junior/senior race; 6th place and the 3rd senior.

I wore the track uniform with a short sleeve shirt and gloves, my torso felt cold during the race so maybe long sleeve would have been better and possibly even a hat, Ari and I got a good spot on the line and there was plenty of space. Given all the rumors of the first mile being super fast, I definitely think I went out too slow (4:55 at the mile, likely the warmup/conditions). Throughout the race I always felt like I was chasing and never packed up with anyone which was to my detriment. I moved up from the mile to 2 mile a bit but it was tough in the woods on the trails. A little after two miles I started to not pass people anymore and basically stayed put. My legs felt cold and lactic in the second half of the woods and the downhills were slow, kinda felt my hamstring then and afterward. I came into the final field with way too much left strength-wise but still couldn't really reach a high gear, I think I passed a few guys though. I was thinking about the front of the race a lot, hoping for good news when I finished.

Overall, I can't be disappointed with 35th. I know this wasn't a great race competitively or even in terms of my fitness, but it was definitely a learning experience and great to run. I didn't really feel as good in the days leading up as before New Englands and I think muscularly I was definitely tighter despite stretching (don't know why... maybe the cold, maybe it's just been a long season). I've had a great season and been consistent but top 25ish would have been sweet.

Chatted with Coach Harwick after, I also saw Coach Dolan but didn't talk to him. Afterward, my dad and I went to Columbia just to see it and walked around, it was really cold and nothing much was happening. Coach B's retirement dinner was later, really cool to see alumni and hear stories, it truly is the end of an era.

And now a note on Ari... He was 3rd!!!!!!!! Made Footlocker!!!!! San Diego!!!!!! I yelled to Max in the chute and couldn't believe it when he held up a three. I didn't even care about how I raced after, it was so cool trying to comprehend it with the other Hall guys. I'm really proud to be teammates/training partners with a Footlocker finalist but even more proud that our hard work and dedication and support since freshman year has opened new doors for us both. Huge viewing party in two weeks!!!!!!!!!

SCALE: 8

Form felt weak and upper body was pretty tight, I dropped the pace because things felt smoother at 6:30ish, not great aerobically either. I'll build up to typical daily mileage this week but real training won't start until next week.

Break went by quickly but I'm glad the non-running part is done now. I went to indoor practice each day and lifted or did functional strength/core. I tried to focus on stability, hamstrings, and single-leg stuff; a lot of lunges with medicine-balls. I paced time-trials for distance underclassmen on Friday; first 800 of the girls 1200 then paced Ryan and Ethan to sub-6 miles (5:51, 5:56-- both PRs), 6-flat pace felt easy and form was okay.
